com.conceptwave.scripting
Class NavTree

com.conceptwave.scripting.Object
  com.conceptwave.scripting.CWScriptable
      com.conceptwave.scripting.CwObject
          com.conceptwave.scripting.Controller
              com.conceptwave.scripting.NavTree

public class NavTree
extends Controller

NavTree is a java object that represents tree node and navigation tree instances at runtime.

The methods listed in the Script Documentation are native java methods available for scripting.
In addition to java native methods NavTree object has variables and script methods defined at the metadata level in the System template:
com.conceptwave.system.TreeNode is the base metadata for tree nodes and
com.conceptwave.system.NavigationTree is the base for navigation trees.

com.conceptwave.system.NavigationTree extends com.conceptwave.system.TreeNode type and it is the root node of the tree. Although tree node and tree are different metadata types, at runtime they are instances of the same NavTree java class.

Moreover com.conceptwave.system.TreeNode extends com.conceptwave.system.UserInterface so tree nodes and the navigation trees themselves inherit variables and methods of the base UI.

For more information please refer to the Help Documentation, section "ConceptWave Documentation > Velocity Studio User Guide > User Interface Modelling > Navigation Trees".

There are several ways to create a Navigation tree in scripts:

 var tree = new NavTree("ns.myNavTree");
 // or
 var tree = new ns.myNavTree();
To instantiate a Navigation Tree with its model counterpart created as well, you may write the following script: 
 //create a model instance, ex. order:
 var order = new ns.order1();
 ...
 //create the navigation tree
 var orderUI = new ns.myOrderTree(order);
 
 // OR specify a parent as well as model
 var orderUI = new ns.myOrderTree(order, parent);
 
 // OR to create a navigation tree UI from the order:
 var orderUI = new order.UserInterface(order, parent);
The parameters of Navigation Tree constructor are as follows:
Parameter 1 is the model (e.g. Document, Finder, Order, etc). If it is a top-level Navigation Tree, set to null.
Parameter 2 is the parent User Interface. Set to null if there is no User Interface to parent relationship.

Another way to create a navigation tree is to use the following generic constructor: 

 var tree = new com.conceptwave.system.NavigationTree(fullName,model,parent)
where fullName is the dot-notation string representation of the object, including the namespace name (eg. "ns.myTree").

Tree node loads its children on-demand.
childNodes is a variable that keeps the array of loaded children.
loadChildren method loads node's children (or re-loads if called for already loaded node), creating tree nodes (controllers) for each object from the tree model.
loaded property of the tree node keeps the load status. Check the status and load children before accessing them: 

 if (!treeNode.loaded) {
    treeNode.loadChildren(); 
    for (var i = 0; i < treeNode.childNodes.length; i++) {
      treeNode[i]...
    }
 }

applyConversionMap

public void applyConversionMap(CwObject sourceModel,
                               CwObject targetModel,
                               String mapName)
Applies conversion map using specified target data object, source data object.
The model data object can be: Document, Finder, DataStructure.
If the model object (can be both source and target) is a finder then the finder's current search document is taken as source/target.

Parameters:
sourceModel - Source data object
targetModel - Target data object
mapName - Conversion map name. Can be null, then the default conversion map will be used.
